)  --done_counting=1--> Wait\n  Wait  (done=1)      --ack=0--> Wait\n  Wait  (done=1)      --ack=1--> S\n\nAt reset, the state machine starts in state "S". Derive next-state logic\nequations and output logic equations by inspection assuming the following\none-hot encoding is used: (S, S1, S11, S110, B0, B1, B2, B3, Count, Wait)\n= (10\'b0000000001, 10\'b0000000010, 10\'b0000000100, ... , 10\'b1000000000)\n\nDerive state transition and output logic equations by inspection assuming\na one-hot encoding. Implement only the state transition logic and output\nlogic (the combinational logic portion) for this state machine.\n\nWrite code that generates the following signals:\n\n - B3_next -- Assert when next-state is B3 state\n - S_next -- Assert when next-state is S state\n - S1_next -- Assert when next-state is S1 state\n - Count_next -- Assert when next-state is Count state\n - Wait_next -- Assert when next-state is Wait state\n - done -- output logic\n - counting -- output logic\n - shift_ena -- output logic\n\n\n</input_spec>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nAnother agent has generated a testbench regarding the given input_spec:\n<testbench>\n`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\n`define OK 12\n`define INCORRECT 13\n\n\nmodule stimulus_gen (\n\tinput clk,\n\toutput reg d,\n\toutput reg done_counting,\n\toutput reg ack,\n\toutput reg [9:0] state,\n\tinput tb_match\n);\n\n\tinitial begin\n\t\t{d, done_counting, ack} <= 3\'h0;\n\t\tstate <= 10\'h0;\n\t\t\n\t\trepeat(300) @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\t\t\t{d, done_counting, ack} = $random;\n\t\t\tstate <= 1<< ($unsigned($random) % 10);\n\t\tend\n\t\t\n\t\t#1 $finish;\n\tend\n\nendmodule\n\nmodule tb();\n\n\ttypedef struct packed {\n\t\tint errors;\n\t\tint errortime;\n\t\tint errors_B3_next;\n\t\tint errortime_B3_next;\n\t\tint errors_S_next;\n\t\tint errortime_S_next;\n\t\tint errors_S1_next;\n\t\tint errortime_S1_next;\n\t\tint errors_Count_next;\n\t\tint errortime_Count_next;\n\t\tint errors_Wait_next;\n\t\tint errortime_Wait_next;\n\t\tint errors_done;\n\t\tint errortime_done;\n\t\tint errors_counting;\n\t\tint errortime_counting;\n\t\tint errors_shift_ena;\n\t\tint errortime_shift_ena;\n\t\t\n\t\tint clocks;\n\t} stats;\n\t\n\tstats stats1;\n\t\n\t\n\twire[511:0] wavedrom_title;\n\twire wavedrom_enable;\n\tint wavedrom_hide_after_time;\n\t\n\treg clk=0;\n\tinitial forever\n\t\t#5 clk = ~clk;\n\n\tlogic d;\n\tlogic done_counting;\n\tlogic ack;\n\tlogic [9:0] state;\n\tlogic B3_next_ref;\n\tlogic B3_next_dut;\n\tlogic S_next_ref;\n\tlogic S_next_dut;\n\tlogic S1_next_ref;\n\tlogic S1_next_dut;\n\tlogic Count_next_ref;\n\tlogic Count_next_dut;\n\tlogic Wait_next_ref;\n\tlogic Wait_next_dut;\n\tlogic done_ref;\n\tlogic done_dut;\n\tlogic counting_ref;\n\tlogic counting_dut;\n\tlogic shift_ena_ref;\n\tlogic shift_ena_dut;\n\n\t// Queue storage declarations\n\t// MAX_QUEUE_SIZE must be <= 10 as per requirement.\n\tlocalparam MAX_QUEUE_SIZE = 10;\n\n\t// Inputs: d (1 bit), done_counting (1 bit), ack (1 bit), state (10 bits). Total 13 bits for easy queueing if grouped.\n\treg [12:0] input_data_queue [$]; \n\t\n\t// Outputs: B3_next, S_next, S1_next, Count_next, Wait_next, done, counting, shift_ena (8 bits)\n\treg [7:0] got_output_queue [$];\n\treg [7:0] golden_output_queue [$];\n\t\n\t// Flags to track first mismatch\n\treg mismatch_detected = 0;\n\n\tinitial begin \n\t\t$dumpfile("wave.vcd");\n\t\t$dumpvars(1, stim1.clk, tb_mismatch, d, done_counting, ack, state, B3_next_ref, B3_next_dut, S_next_ref, S_next_dut, S1_next_ref, S1_next_dut, Count_next_ref, Count_next_dut, Wait_next_ref, Wait_next_dut, done_ref, done_dut, counting_ref, counting_dut, shift_ena_ref, shift_ena_dut );\n\tend\n\n\n\twire tb_match;\n\twire tb_mismatch = ~tb_match;\n\t\n\nstimulus_gen stim1 (\n\t\t.clk, \n\t\t.* , \n\t\td.d, \n\t\tdone_counting, \n\t\tack,\n\t\t.state );\n\tRefModule good1 (\n\t\td.d, \n\t\tdone_counting,\n\t\tack,\n\t\t.state,\n\t\t.B3_next(B3_next_ref),\n\t\t.S_next(S_next_ref),\n\t\t.S1_next(S1_next_ref),\n\t\t.Count_next(Count_next_ref),\n\t\t.Wait_next(Wait_next_ref),\n\t\tdone(done_ref),\n\t\t.counting(counting_ref),\n\t\t.shift_ena(shift_ena_ref) );\n\t\n\tTopModule top_module1 (\n\t\td.d,\n\t\tdone_counting,\n\t\tack,\n\t\t.state,\n\t\t.B3_next(B3_next_dut),\n\t\t.S_next(S_next_dut),\n\t\t.S1_next(S1_next_dut),\n\t\t.Count_next(Count_next_dut),\n\t\t.Wait_next(Wait_next_dut),\n\t\tdone(done_dut),\n\t\t.counting(counting_dut),\n\t\t.shift_ena(shift_ena_dut) );\n\n\t\n\t// --- Task Definitions ---\n\ttask wait_for_end_of_timestep;\n\t\trepeat(5) begin\n\t\tstrobe <= !strobe;  // Try to delay until the very end of the time step.\n\t\t@(strobe);\n\t\tendtask\n\n\t// Helper function to display queued data upon first error\n\ntask display_mismatch_info;\n\tbegin\n\t\t$display("========================================================================================");\n\t\t$display("!!! FIRST MISMATCH DETECTED AT TIME %0t !!!", $time);\n\t\t$display("Total mismatches counted so far: %0d", stats1.errors);\n\t\t$display("Displaying the last %0d cycles stored in the queue.", input_data_queue.size());\n\t\t$display("========================================================================================");\n\t\t\n\t\tfor (int i = 0; i < input_data_queue.size(); i++) begin\n\t\t\t// Extract relevant signals from the packed queue element\n\t\t\treg [2:0] q_d_ack_done = input_data_queue[i][2:0];\n\t\t\treg [9:0] q_state = input_data_queue[i][12:3];\n\t\t\treg [7:0] q_got_out = got_output_queue[i];\n\t\t\treg [7:0] q_golden_out = golden_output_queue[i];\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t$display("\\n--- CYCLE %0d (Time: %0t ps) ---", i, $time);\n\t\t\t// Display Inputs\n\t\t\t$display("Inputs: d=%b, done_counting=%b, ack=%b, state=0x%0h (%0d)", q_d_ack_done[0], q_d_ack_done[1], q_d_ack_done[2], q_state, q_state);\n\t\t\t// Display Reference Outputs (Golden)\n\t\t\t$display("Golden Outputs (Ref): 0x%0h (%b)", q_golden_out, q_golden_out);\n\t\t\t// Display DUT Outputs (Got)\n\t\t\t$display("DUT Outputs (Got): 0x%0h (%b)", q_got_out, q_got_out);\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t// Detailed signal check for the current cycle (optional, but helpful for first error)\n\t\t\t$display("Detailed Signal Check (Bit-by-Bit): ");\n\t\t\t$display("  B3_next: Ref=%b, Got=%b", q_golden_out[0], q_got_out[0]);\n\t\t\t$display("  S_next: Ref=%b, Got=%b", q_golden_out[1], q_got_out[1]);\n\t\t\t$display("  S1_next: Ref=%b, Got=%b", q_golden_out[2], q_got_out[2]);\n\t\t\t$display("  Count_next: Ref=%b, Got=%b", q_golden_out[3], q_got_out[3]);\n\t\t\t$display("  Wait_next: Ref=%b, Got=%b", q_golden_out[4], q_got_out[4]);\n\t\t\t$display("  done: Ref=%b, Got=%b", q_golden_out[5], q_got_out[5]);\n\t\t\t$display("  counting: Ref=%b, Got=%b", q_golden_out[6], q_got_out[6]);\n\t\t\t$display("  shift_ena: Ref=%b, Got=%b", q_golden_out[7], q_got_out[7]);\n\t\t\t\n\t\tend\n\tendtask\n\n\t// --- Simulation Logic ---\n\t\n\t// Verification: XORs on the right makes any X in good_vector match anything, but X in dut_vector will only match X.\n\tassign tb_match = ( { B3_next_ref, S_next_ref, S1_next_ref, Count_next_ref, Wait_next_ref, done_ref, counting_ref, shift_ena_ref } === ( { B3_next_ref, S_next_ref, S1_next_ref, Count_next_ref, Wait_next_ref, done_ref, counting_ref, shift_ena_ref } ^ { B3_next_dut, S_next_dut, S1_next_dut, Count_next_dut, Wait_next_dut, done_dut, counting_dut, shift_ena_dut } ^ { B3_next_ref, S_next_ref, S1_next_ref, Count_next_ref, Wait_next_ref, done_ref, counting_ref, shift_ena_ref } ) );\n\t\n\t// Sequential logic processing, Queue management, and Error Checking\n\talways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\t\tif (!mismatch_detected) begin\n\t\t\t// 1. Store Inputs\n\t\t\t// d, done_counting, ack (3 bits) | state (10 bits)\n\t\t\tinput_data_queue.push_back({state, done_counting, ack, d});\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t// 2. Store DUT Outputs\n\t\t\tgot_output_queue.push_back({B3_next_dut, S_next_dut, S1_next_dut, Count_next_dut, Wait_next_dut, done_dut, counting_dut, shift_ena_dut});\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t// 3. Store Reference Outputs\n\t\t\tgolden_output_queue.push_back({B3_next_ref, S_next_ref, S1_next_ref, Count_next_ref, Wait_next_ref, done_ref, counting_ref, shift_ena_ref});\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t// 4. Check Mismatch\n\t\t\tif (!tb_match) begin\n\t\t\t\tstats1.errors++;\n\t\t\t\tif (stats1.errors == 1) begin\n\t\t\t\t\tmismatch_detected = 1;\n\t\t\t\t\tdisplay_mismatch_info();\n\t\t\t\tend\n\t\t\tend\n\t\tend\n\t\t\n\t\t// 5. Manage Queue Size\n\t\t\tif (input_data_queue.size() >= MAX_QUEUE_SIZE) begin\n\t\t\tinput_data_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgot_output_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgolden_output_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\tend\n\t\tend\n\t\tend\n\n\t// Original Error Counting (Kept for total error tally, though detailed info is in queue display)\n\talways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\t\tstats1.clocks++;\n\t\tif (!tb_match) begin\n\t\t\tif (stats1.errors == 1) stats1.errortime = $time;\n\t\tend\n\t\t\n\t\t// Checking individual signals for stats1 counters\n\t\tif (B3_next_ref !== ( B3_next_ref ^ B3_next_dut ^ B3_next_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_B3_next == 0) stats1.errortime_B3_next = $time;\n\t\t\tsstats1.errors_B3_next = stats1.errors_B3_next+1\'b1; end\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (S_next_ref !== ( S_next_ref ^ S_next_dut ^ S_next_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_S_next == 0) stats1.errortime_S_next = $time;\n\t\t\tsstats1.errors_S_next = stats1.errors_S_next+1\'b1; end\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (S1_next_ref !== ( S1_next_ref ^ S1_next_dut ^ S1_next_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_S1_next == 0) stats1.errortime_S1_next = $time;\n\t\t\tsstats1.errors_S1_next = stats1.errors_S1_next+1\'b1; end\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (Count_next_ref !== ( Count_next_ref ^ Count_next_dut ^ Count_next_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_Count_next == 0) stats1.errortime_Count_next = $time;\n\t\t\tsstats1.errors_Count_next = stats1.errors_Count_next+1\'b1; end\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (Wait_next_ref !== ( Wait_next_ref ^ Wait_next_dut ^ Wait_next_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_Wait_next == 0) stats1.errortime_Wait_next = $time;\n\t\t\tsstats1.errors_Wait_next = stats1.errors_Wait_next+1\'b1; end\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (done_ref !== ( done_ref ^ done_dut ^ done_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_done == 0) stats1.errortime_done = $time;\n\t\t\tsstats1.errors_done = stats1.errors_done+1\'b1; end\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (counting_ref !== ( counting_ref ^ counting_dut ^ counting_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_counting == 0) stats1.errortime_counting = $time;\n\t\t\tsstats1.errors_counting = stats1.errors_counting+1\'b1; end\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (shift_ena_ref !== ( shift_ena_ref ^ shift_ena_dut ^ shift_ena_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_shift_ena == 0) stats1.errortime_shift_ena = $time;\n\t\t\tsstats1.errors_shift_ena = stats1.errors_shift_ena+1\'b1; end\n\t\tend\n\tend\n\n\t// add timeout after 100K cycles\n\tinitial begin\n\t\t#1000000\n\t\t$display("\\n========================================================================================");\n\t\t$display("TIMEOUT REACHED. SIMULATION TERMINATING.");\n\t\t$display("========================================================================================");\n\t\t$finish();\n\tend\n\n\t// Final reporting logic\n\tinitial begin\n\t\t@(negedge clk);\n\t\t#1;\n\t\tif (stats1.errors == 0) begin\n\t\t\ts$display("\\n========================================================================================");\n\t\t\ts$display("SIMULATION PASSED");\n\t\t\ts$display("========================================================================================");\n\t\tend else begin\n\t\t\ts$display("\\n========================================================================================");\n\t\t\ts$display("SIMULATION FAILED - %0d MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME %0d", stats1.errors, stats1.errortime);\n\t\t\ts$display("========================================================================================");\n\t\tend\n\t\t$display("Simulation finished at %0d ps", $time);\n\tend\n\nendmodule\n</testbench>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nThe module interface is given below:\n<module_interface>\nmodule TopModule (\n    input d,\n    input done_counting,\n    input ack,\n    input [9:0] state,\n    output B3_next,\n    output S_next,\n    output S1_next,\n    output Count_next,\n    output Wait_next,\n    output done,\n    output counting,\n    output shift_ena\n);\nendmodule\n</module_interface>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.ASSISTANT: 'assistant'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='{\n    "reasoning": "The goal is to implement a Moore state machine with 10 states using a one-hot encoding scheme. The state inputs are d, done_counting, and ack. The state register is 10 bits wide, representing the 10 defined states: S, S1, S11, S110, B0, B1, B2, B3, Count, Wait.\\n\\n1. **State Encoding**: The problem specifies a one-hot encoding. We must map the 10 states to specific 10-bit values. The provided hints give a partial mapping: S=10\'b0000000001, S1=10\'b0000000010, S11=10\'b0000000100, and the last state Wait=10\'b1000000000. We need to derive the remaining states (S110, B0, B1, B2, B3, Count) to complete the one-hot set.\\n\\n   Let\'s establish the mapping based on the structure and the provided examples:\\n   - S: 10\'b0000000001 (State 1)\\n   - S1: 10\'b0000000010 (State 2)\\n   - S11: 10\'b0000000100 (State 4)\\n   - S110: Must be State 8 (to maintain spacing/simplicity if possible, but we\'ll derive based on transitions).\\n   - B0: State 16?\\n   - B1: State 32?\\n   - B2: State 64?\\n   - B3: State 128?\\n   - Count: State 256?\\n   - Wait: 10\'b1000000000 (State 512, or index 9 if 0-indexed, but the hint suggests a specific bit pattern for Wait)\\n\\n   Since the problem mandates a one-hot encoding for 10 states, we will use indices 0 through 9 for the states, and assign the corresponding power of 2 to the state register, ensuring only one bit is set per state.\\n\\n   Let\'s assign indices 0 to 9 to the states in the order they appear in the transition table (S, S1, S11, S110, B0, B1, B2, B3, Count, Wait) and use the index value as the state encoding.\\n\\n   State Mapping (Index $\\\\rightarrow$ One-Hot Value):\\n   Index 0 (S) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0000000001\\n   Index 1 (S1) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0000000010\\n   Index 2 (S11) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0000000100\\n   Index 3 (S110) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0000001000\\n   Index 4 (B0) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0001000000\\n   Index 5 (B1) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0010000000\\n   Index 6 (B2) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0100000000\\n   Index 7 (B3) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b1000000000 (Wait state hint used here, need to check)\\n   Index 8 (Count) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0000000000 (Wait state hint used here, need to check)\\n   Index 9 (Wait) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b1000000000 (Wait state hint used here)\\n\\n   *Revisiting the hint*: The hint states: (S, S1, S11, S110, B0, B1, B2, B3, Count, Wait) = (10\'b0000000001, 10\'b0000000010, 10\'b0000000100, ..., 10\'b1000000000). This implies the states are ordered in the tuple, and the last state (Wait) is 10\'b1000000000. Let\'s assume the mapping is sequential based on the tuple order, and fill in the rest sequentially.\\n\\n   Let the states be $State_0, State_1, \\forall \\text{etc.} \\rightarrow State_9$. \\n   $State_0 (S) = 10\'b0000000001$\\n   $State_1 (S1) = 10\'b0000000010$\\n   $State_2 (S11) = 10\'b0000000100$\\n   $State_9 (Wait) = 10\'b1000000000$\\n\\n   We must ensure that the state transitions are correct using these values. Since the implementation only requires *next-state logic* and *output logic* (combinational), we will use `case` statements on the current `state` register value, which is the standard approach for one-hot FSMs.\\n\\n2. **State Register Logic (Sequential)**: We need an `always @(posedge clk)` block. The next state logic (`state_next`) will be derived combinatorially. The current state (`state`) will be registered to `state_next` on the clock edge, subject to the reset condition (which isn\'t explicitly defined for the state register, but the specification implies a starting state \'S\' at reset, so we\'ll use synchronous reset to $S$).\\n\\n3. **Next State Logic (Combinational)**: We derive the next state based on the current `state` and inputs (d, done_counting, ack). We use a `case (state)` structure. For each state, we check the input conditions to determine the next state value.\\n\\n4. **Output Logic (Combinational)**: We derive the outputs (done, counting, shift_ena) based on the *current* state (Moore machine). The next-state outputs ($B3_{next}, S_{next}, \\text{etc.}$) are derived combinatorially based on the current state and inputs, as they represent the *target* state.\\n\\n**Implementation Details**: \\n- States are mapped using `localparam` for readability.\\n- The state register (`state`) is declared as `logic [9:0]` and initialized in an `initial` block to the reset state \'S\'.\\n- Next state logic determines `state_next` based on transitions.\\n- Output logic determines the required next-state signals ($B3_{next}, S_{next}, \\text{etc.}$) and the instantaneous outputs (done, counting, shift_ena).\\n\\n**Syntax Advice**: \\n- Use `logic` for all signals. \\n- Use `always @(*)` for all combinational blocks (next state logic, output logic). \\n- Avoid explicit reset logic for intermediate wires/registers if they can be correctly driven by the combinational logic (like $B3_{next}$), but the main state register *must* be reset.\\n- The next-state signals ($B3_{next}, \\text{etc.}$) are essentially boolean flags indicating which state the FSM is *moving to* in the next clock cycle, which must be generated combinatorially based on the current state/inputs.\\n\\n**State Derivations (Crucial Step)**:\\n*   **Reset**: Start in S ($State_0$).\\n*   **Transitions (Next State $State_{