responding power of 2 to the state register, ensuring only one bit is set per state.\\n\\n   Let\'s assign indices 0 to 9 to the states in the order they appear in the transition table (S, S1, S11, S110, B0, B1, B2, B3, Count, Wait) and use the index value as the state encoding.\\n\\n   State Mapping (Index $\\\\rightarrow$ One-Hot Value):\\n   Index 0 (S) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0000000001\\n   Index 1 (S1) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0000000010\\n   Index 2 (S11) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0000000100\\n   Index 3 (S110) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0000001000\\n   Index 4 (B0) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0001000000\\n   Index 5 (B1) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0010000000\\n   Index 6 (B2) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0100000000\\n   Index 7 (B3) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b1000000000 (Wait state hint used here, need to check)\\n   Index 8 (Count) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b0000000000 (Wait state hint used here, need to check)\\n   Index 9 (Wait) $\\\\rightarrow$ 10\'b1000000000 (Wait state hint used here)\\n\\n   *Revisiting the hint*: The hint states: (S, S1, S11, S110, B0, B1, B2, B3, Count, Wait) = (10\'b0000000001, 10\'b0000000010, 10\'b0000000100, ..., 10\'b1000000000). This implies the states are ordered in the tuple, and the last state (Wait) is 10\'b1000000000. Let\'s assume the mapping is sequential based on the tuple order, and fill in the rest sequentially.\\n\\n   Let the states be $State_0, State_1, \\forall \\text{etc.} \\rightarrow State_9$. \\n   $State_0 (S) = 10\'b0000000001$\\n   $State_1 (S1) = 10\'b0000000010$\\n   $State_2 (S11) = 10\'b0000000100$\\n   $State_9 (Wait) = 10\'b1000000000$\\n\\n   We must ensure that the state transitions are correct using these values. Since the implementation only requires *next-state logic* and *output logic* (combinational), we will use `case` statements on the current `state` register value, which is the standard approach for one-hot FSMs.\\n\\n2. **State Register Logic (Sequential)**: We need an `always @(posedge clk)` block. The next state logic (`state_